h3. Issue Summary

This issue is a copy of [https://ecosystem.atlassian.net/browse/ACJIRA-2291.]
{quote}Hi team,

I am working on Check content permissions (page) and when testing I have always true even the user does not has permission with delete operation.

Example user does not have permission to delete Confluence page but when checking with rest api hasPermission is true!!!

Any help!

[https://developer.atlassian.com/cloud/confluence/rest/api-group-content-permissions/#api-api-content-id-permission-check-post]
{quote}
h3. Steps to Reproduce
 # Create a Confluence Space
 # Grant the confluence-users group the below space permissions:  !Screen Shot 2021-12-20 at 12.07.28 PM.png|width=729,height=22!
 # Add a user to the *confluence_user* group and only this group
 # In the created Confluence Space, create a page and attach an attachment.
 # Run the [Check Content Permissions API request|https://developer.atlassian.com/cloud/confluence/rest/api-group-content-permissions/#api-wiki-rest-api-content-id-permission-check-post] with the below payload on the {*}attachments contentID{*}:
{code:java}
payload = json.dumps( {
  "subject": {
    "type": "user",
    "identifier": "<Atlassian-Account-ID>"
  },
  "operation": "update"
} )
{code}

 # The JSON output is:
{code:java}
{
    "_links": {
        "base": "https://ispann.atlassian.net/wiki",
        "context": "/wiki"
    },
    "errors": [],
    "hasPermission": true
}
{code}

 # It is expected that this user should have *"hasPermission": false* as the *confluence-users* group doesn't have permission to *update* attachments as the group doesn't have *add/delete attachment space permissions*

h3. Expected Results
{code:java}
{"hasPermission":false,"errors":[

{"key":"content.permission.check.user.no.content.permission","translation":"User does not have permission to the content","args":[]}
{code}
h3. Actual Results
{code:java}
    "errors": [],
    "hasPermission": true
{code}
h3. Workaround

Currently no workaround

h3. Issue Summary
The preview feature we can use while editing a page is awesome, as it lets us have an idea about how the content will look like after publishing the page. 
Sometimes, when you go to the preview mode, and then back to edit the page, the cursor is not exactly where we were when editing the content.

h3. Steps to Reproduce
# Generate 30 [Lorem Ipsum|https://www.lipsum.com/] paragraphs;
# Paste them into a new page;
# In the middle of the text, place a header or an image (just as a placeholder);
# Preview the page (*CTRL + Shift + E*, for Windows / *Command + Shift + E*, for Mac);
# Back to the editing mode (press *E*).

h3. Expected Results
You got back to the exact same place you were with the cursor while editing the page.

h3. Actual Results
One of the below three behaviors can happen:
* The text where your cursor was gets placed at the top of the page;
* The place where the cursor was is a little above the range you actually is (you need to scroll up to find it);
* You got back to the same place you were, but the cursor is not selected on the page.

*Notes*:
* Sometimes it behaves as expected, which makes this issue quite intermitent.

h3. Workaround
Currently there is no known workaround for this behavior. A workaround will be added here when available

h3. Issue Summary

Marketplace Partner reported issue on the Developer Community https://community.developer.atlassian.com/t/copy-single-page-api-with-custom-body-does-not-work-anymore/43714

We are experiencing a major problem with the Copy single page API. One of the core features of our app (Scroll Documents) is to create copies of pages (or rather page trees) where include macros are resolved, so the macros are replaced by the actual content of the included page, and any attachments referenced by the included page are copied over.
h3. Steps to Reproduce

Imagine you have a Page A and a Page B. Page A contains an include macro that includes page B. Now you want to create a copy of Page A (called Page A*) where the include macro is resolved. The way our app does this is:
 # Fetch Page A, parse the storage format and look for include macros
 # Discover the include macro pointing to Page B, so fetch Page B and replace the macro with the body of page B in the parsed body of Page A
 # Now copy Page A to Page A* by using the Copy single page API (using a {{parent_page}} destination). Specify the parsed body of Page A with the replaced include macro as a custom {{body}} during the copy operation.
 # Look at the body of Page B and see if it references any attachments attached to itself. If it does, use the Copy single page API with an {{existing_page}} target to copy Page B to Page A*, with {{copyAttachments: true}} and specifying the body of Page A* as a custom {{body}} for the copy operation. This will copy all attachments of Page B to Page A* (which is needed because they are referenced in the included content), without changing the body of Page A*.

While this definitely worked back when I was developing this feature, we just discovered by accident that step 3 doesn’t work anymore as intended. I don’t know for how long this has been the case, but I hope for not too long, because this breaks one of the core features of our app without being immediately noticeable (because include macros are not identifiable when viewing the page).

 

For reference, here are the two exact requests that we are doing:

 

{{}}
{code:java}

{code}
{{POST https://cdauth.atlassian.net/wiki/rest/api/content/1182859265/copy?expand=children.attachment.version%2Cbody.storage%2Cmetadata.properties.K15tDocsPage%2Cversion%2Cspace}}
{{ }}
{{{ "copyAttachments" : true, "copyPermissions" : false, "copyProperties" : false, "copyLabels" : true, "copyCustomContents" : false, "destination" : { "type" : "parent_page", "value" : "1185349633" }, "pageTitle" : "(v24) Include test", "body" : { "storage" : { "value" : "<p>Test content 1</p>", "representation" : "storage" }, "raw" : null } } }}

 

 

{{}}
{code:java}

{code}
{{POST https://cdauth.atlassian.net/wiki/rest/api/content/1179582465/copy?expand=children.attachment.version%2Cbody.storage%2Cmetadata.properties.K15tDocsPage%2Cversion%2Cspace }}

{{{ "copyAttachments" : true, "copyPermissions" : false, "copyProperties" : false, "copyLabels" : false, "copyCustomContents" : false, "destination" : { "type" : "existing_page", "value" : "2023293113" }, "pageTitle" : "(v24) Include test", "body" : { "storage" : { "value" : "<p>Test content 2</p>", "representation" : "storage" }, "raw" : null } } }}

 
h3. Expected Results

Page is copies completely
h3. Actual Results

What seems to happen is that in step 3, when specifying a custom body using a parent_page copy destination, that custom body is ignored the the body of the target page is the same as the body of the source page. However, in step 4, when specifying a custom body using an existing_page copy destination, specifying the custom body seems to work.

 
h3. Workaround

Currently there is no known workaround for this behavior. A workaround will be added here when available

h3. Issue Summary
Copying a page via API is an awesome way to automate some of our daily tasks! It seems that sometimes when we need to copy a page but change its body, the endpoint does not respect our changes and just copy the content from the original page.

h3. Steps to Reproduce
# Create a page with some text content;
# Use the [copy page API|https://developer.atlassian.com/cloud/confluence/rest/api-group-content---children-and-descendants/#api-api-content-id-copy-post] to copy the page you created (change some of the fields from the below curl and run it on a terminal):
{code:curl}curl --request POST \
  --url 'https://<SITE_NAME>.atlassian.net/wiki/rest/api/content/<CONTENT_ID>/copy' \
  --user '<EMAIL:API_TOKEN>' \
  --header 'Accept: application/json;charset=UTF-8' \
  --header 'Content-Type: application/json' \
  --data '{
  "destination": {
    "type": "parent_page",
    "value": "<CONTENT_ID>"
  },
  "pageTitle": "Page copied via API",
  "body": {
    "storage": {
      "value": "This text should appear in the new copied page instead of the same content the original page has",
      "representation": "storage"
    }
  }
}'{code}

h3. Expected Results
Even copying the page, the body of the page should be changed to what we set in the {{body}} parameter.

h3. Actual Results
The page is just copied with no changes.

h3. Workaround
Currently there is no known workaround for this behavior. A workaround will be added here when available

h3. Issue Summary

With the new inline comments feature, working on Confluence got easier with the possibility to add these comments from within the editor. 
 Though that's a great feature, it seems it is not working well when an inline comment is being added within a third-party macro.
h3. Steps to Reproduce
 # Install one of the below third-party add-ons on Confluence (for example):
 ** [Numbered Headings|https://marketplace.atlassian.com/apps/16063/numbered-headings?hosting=cloud&tab=overview];
 ** [Table Filter and Charts for Confluence|https://marketplace.atlassian.com/apps/27447/table-filter-and-charts-for-confluence?hosting=cloud&tab=overview];
 # Create a new page;
 # Insert a macro from one of the installed add-ons;
 # After typing some text within the macros, add an inline comment somewhere in this text;
 # Publish the page.

h3. Expected Results

The inline comment is being shown in the text.
h3. Actual Results

No inline comment can be seen.

*Notes*:
 * It might be happening with other different third-party macros - the 2 mentioned above are just as an example, since they were macros we tested this behavior;
 * From the published page, if we add {{?focusedCommentId=COMMENT_ID#comment-COMMENT_ID}} at the end of the URL, the comment gets shown at the right side of the screen.

h3. Workaround

Currently there is no known workaround for this behavior, but removing the content from within the macros will get the inline comment shown in the text.
